{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568707"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21301"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21301"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.1,0.1,0.01,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102238"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14174"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84702"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102238"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset left-sided crushing chest pain. He has jugular vein distension during inspiration and a systolic blood pressure of 70 mmHg by palpation with clear lung fields. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His regular medications are perindopril and atorvastatin. He does not smoke and does not drink alcohol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 56/min, blood pressure 70/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiac auscultation is normal. There are no added sounds or murmurs. Lung fields are clear to auscultation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG is performed. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["250-500 mL isotonic saline rapidly","Intravenous dobutamine","Intravenous morphine","Intravenous frusemide","Intravenous nitroglycerine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with ECG changes consistent with an inferior ST elevation myocardial infarction - with ST elevation in leads II, III and AVF. Hypotension, jugular venous distention and ST changes to V4R-V6R further suggest right ventricular involvement as a complication of an inferior STEMI. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe right ventricle is preload dependent, and hypotension in this context is often due to impaired right ventricular filling and output. \u003Cstrong\u003E250-500 mL isotonic saline rapidly\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important next step to increase preload and improve cardiac output. Careful monitoring is required to avoid fluid overload, but initial cautious fluid resuscitation is the mainstay of early management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dobutamine\u003C/strong\u003E is an inotrope that may be considered if hypotension persists despite adequate fluid resuscitation, but it is not the first-line intervention. Inotropes are reserved for refractory shock after preload has been optimised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous morphine\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used for pain relief in myocardial infarction, but it can cause vasodilation and worsen hypotension, especially in right ventricular infarction. It does not address the underlying haemodynamic compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous frusemide\u003C/strong\u003E is a diuretic and is contraindicated in right ventricular infarction with hypotension and clear lungs, as it will further reduce preload and worsen shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous nitroglycerine\u003C/strong\u003E is a vasodilator that reduces preload and is contraindicated in right ventricular infarction, as it can precipitate profound hypotension and cardiovascular collapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERight ventricular infarction should be suspected in any patient with inferior myocardial infarction and hypotension with clear lungs. Early recognition and appropriate fluid resuscitation are critical to stabilise the patient before definitive reperfusion therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Right ventricular infarction should be suspected in patients with inferior ST elevation myocardial infarction and hypotension with clear lung fields.","Initial management of right ventricular infarction includes cautious fluid resuscitation to optimise preload.","Vasodilators and diuretics are contraindicated in right ventricular infarction due to risk of worsening hypotension."],"references":["Byrne RA, Rossello X, Coughlan JJ, et al. 2023 ESC Guidelines for the management of acute coronary syndromes [published correction appears in Eur Heart J. 2024 Apr 1;45(13):1145. doi: 10.1093/eurheartj/ehad870.]. Eur Heart J. 2023;44(38):3720-3826. doi:10.1093/eurheartj/ehad191","Chang Q, Xu Z, Liu R. Acute Inferior Wall Myocardial Infarction: What Is the Culprit Artery?. Circulation. 2021;144(23):1893-1895. doi:10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.057659"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84702"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21301"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21870"}]},"explanati